## Breeding

Oscars are substrate spawners that form pair bonds over time. Breeding requires:

**Natural pair formation:** Allow a group of 4–6 young Oscars to grow together. Natural pairs form through mutual selection. Forced pairings from two random adults often result in aggression, not bonding.

**Tank preparation:** A 450+ litre breeding tank. Flat stones or slate tiles provide spawning surfaces. Minimal other fish in the tank.

**Pre-spawn behaviour:** The pair engages in elaborate mutual display — fin spreading, circling, body quivering. "Kissing" (lip-locking) in established pairs is affectionate pair bonding, not combat.

**Egg deposition:** 1,000–3,000 eggs on cleaned flat surfaces. Both parents fan and guard eggs aggressively.

**Hatching:** 2–3 days at 27°C.

**Fry care:** Parents move wriggling fry to pre-dug pits in the substrate. Fry become free-swimming at 4–5 days post-hatch. Both parents guard fry for 4–6 weeks — extraordinarily long by cichlid standards.

**First foods:**
- **Baby Brine Shrimp** from day 3 of free swimming. **[Live BBS from Blackwater Aquatics](https://blackwateraquatics.ca/collections/live-foods).**
- **Microworms** — Excellent for days 3–14. **[Available at Blackwater Aquatics](https://blackwateraquatics.ca/collections/live-foods).**
- Crushed pellets at week 3

